package.  The tether would then catapault the payload into high orbit.  In doing so, however, the massive hub would lose altitude.  For stationkeeping the hub must tap earth's tenuous electromagnetic field and use it to boost its orbit.  This type of propulsion is called &quot;electrodynamic stationkeeping&quot; and can be used to maintain, raise, or lower an orbit without the use of rocket propellant, so long as the planet has a magnetic field.<br>
<br>
I've attempted to design a Rotavator with electrodynamic stationkeeping for a payload launch capacity of 50 tonnes per hour, for the purpose of construction of a large interstellar starship.  The amount of power needed to maintain orbit is approximately 2.7 Gigawatts, assuming both the electrodynamic stationkeeping engines and the powerplant are working at 100 percent efficiency.<br>
<br>
Can anyone here please estimate the mass, and other important aspects, of constructing a 2.7 Gigawatt nuclear-electric powerplant at an orbit altitude of 4000 km. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uarkuunaves.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ArkuunAves</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 33<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/30/02 5:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=144.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: New Application for Nuclear Power in Space</span><hr size=1> This would greatly depend on the type of reactor.<br>
<br>
If youw ere going to try to use what's used for commercial power today, with Pressure Water Reactors having the highest density...eep.<br>
<br>
A 1000 Megawatt (1 Gigawatt) PWR is pretty dang big, and containment walls are based upon having about 7-9 feet of steel-reinforced-concrete in addition to 1/4-1/2 inch stainless steel inner plating.  Fuel assemblies weigh over 1000 pounds each, with over a hundred in use in the core.  It's closer to 2000 lbs honestly.  And that's spent fuel, with partial depletion.  I don't remember offhand the weight of new fuel.  Each require ~ 14 feet height clearance.  They also need to be replaced every 18 months or so.<br>
<br>
Our most modern PWRs are about the same size, a bit bigger core actually, and produce maybe up to half of what you're looking for...that'd be stretching it.  You'd need 2 of these.<br>
<br>
As a rough ballpark guess...based upon what you'd need for core vessel as well as turbines and generator and whatnot...I'm gonna say, without even hazarding a guess as to mass, that you'd need a minimum of a few acres of space for this.<br>
